                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d531">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.76/19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-04-19T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 19, 1934—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 19—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>182. Shanghai’s April 17, 2 p.m.<note n="61" xml:id="d531fn61">Not
                        printed.</note> Legation has replied as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“April 19, 9 a.m. Your April 17, 2 p.m. From the information available
                            the Legation believes that you should refrain from suggesting <pb
                                facs="0718" n="628" xml:id="pg_628"/> that Americans register their
                            receiving sets. It does not believe that the provisions of the
                            resolution cited in your telegram are applicable.</p>
                        <p>The Legation believes that you should inform the Bureau of International
                            Telegraphs of the inquiries you have received and request to be supplied
                            with a copy of the regulations requiring such registration. You might
                            request to be informed under what authority such regulations were issued
                            and remind the Bureau that you are not in a position to advise Americans
                            to register their sets until the matter has been submitted to the
                            Legation and has received its approval.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
